===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{liushu|p}} of a tool—chisel, awl, spike—used to mark slaves and criminals. The characters {{zh-l|*䇂}} and [[亲]] are two variants. The former (䇂) is the original version, while the latter is a conflation of both 亲 and [[𣓀]], a chisel over a tree to indicate the [[hazelnut]] branch which was flexible enough to be used as a whip.

It appears as [[立]] on the top of characters such as [[妾]], [[竟]], and [[童]]. Unrelated to [[音]] and [[競]], in which it represents the tip of a tongue on top of an open mouth. See also [[辡]]. See also the top component of [[商]].

===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*m-sin||liver; heart; bile; bitter}}; compare {{cog|bo|མཆིན||liver}}, {{cog|my|သည်း||liver}}, {{cog|txg|𗮰||liver}} ({{zh-ref|Gong, 2002}}; {{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}; STEDT).

